# User-Facing Language (pt-BR)

Eco Wallet is a Brazilian product. All copy that end users see MUST be **Brazilian Portuguese (`pt-BR`)** only. Do not ship English (or other locales) in the product UI unless the user explicitly requests multilingual support.

## In scope (pt-BR required)

- Screen titles, headings, body text, hints, placeholders, and tooltips
- Buttons, links, tabs, chips, badges, and navigation labels
- Empty, loading, and error states shown in the app
- Dialogs, sheets, snackbars, toasts, and inline validation messages
- Onboarding, permissions, and settings explanations
- Push notification text and deep-link landing copy (when added)
- User-visible API or GraphQL error messages and field validation text returned to clients

## Out of scope (English is fine)

- Agent instructions, PRDs, TechSpecs, tasks, ADRs, commits, PRs, and code review comments
- Code identifiers: class names, variables, routes, keys, logs, and developer comments
- Internal-only admin or ops tools not shipped to end users (unless specified otherwise)

## Writing guidelines

- Use natural Brazilian Portuguese, not literal translation from English. Prefer terms users expect (e.g. **Entrar**, **Cadastrar**, **Salvar**, **Tentar novamente**).
- Use **você** (or neutral UI phrasing); avoid European Portuguese forms and overly formal **senhor(a)** unless the product tone requires it.
- Format numbers, currency, and dates for Brazil: `R$`, comma as decimal separator when displaying amounts, and locale-aware date/time formatting (`pt_BR`).
- Sentence case for short UI labels is acceptable; use consistent capitalization within a screen.
- Keep strings short and scannable on mobile. Avoid English product jargon when a common Portuguese term exists.

## Implementation

- Prefer a single source of truth for copy (e.g. ARB/`intl` code generation in Flutter, or a shared messages module in web) instead of hard-coding duplicate strings.
- When adding tests that assert UI text, assert the **pt-BR** string, not an English placeholder.
- If existing UI copy is in English, replace it with pt-BR as part of the same change—do not add new English strings.

## Review checklist

Before marking UI work complete, confirm no user-visible English remains on touched screens and that formatting matches Brazilian conventions.
